At a March 17, 2009 launch for Globe Telecom’s cable station in Ballesteros, President Arroyo held the ends of two oversized blue cables as representatives from Globe and India’s Tata Communications brought them together. Located more than 250 miles north of the hotel ballroom in Metro Manila where the ceremony took place, the Ballesteros station provides redundancy for existing cable infrastructure in southern Luzon, some of which was disrupted by the 2006 earthquake off the coast of Taiwan. It joins Tata’s Asian and Pacific networks to a system of terrestrial lines that weave south, roughly following the path of the country’s longest river, used for centuries to transport crops that grow along its shores. The small tobacco-producing community of Ballesteros is a few miles west of the river mouth, a safe distance from the flooding that occurs during monsoon season.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Built to receive the 2013 Southeast Asia Japan Cable, this station is controlled by the Brunei government in partnership with two telecom companies. Although it seems secluded, the town of Telisai is well connected by a coastal highway to neighboring districts. These include the country’s largest oil field, which produced its millionth barrel in 1991. Follow the road thirty miles east, and you will reach the main cable hub in Tungku. But first you’ll first pass the twin antennas of Brunei’s first satellite earth station, set up in 1979 and visible through a barbed wire fence. What appear to be snowdrifts on the hills around you are in fact silica sand deposits, formed long ago when sea levels were higher. Besides its white dunes, the region is perhaps best known for carnivorous pitcher plants, some of which are used in local cuisine.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The small town of Nasugbu, strategically located on the South China Sea only sixty miles from Metro Manila, is the largest network hub in the Philippines. In the 1990s, the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company opened the country’s first international cable station, which towers over the palm trees and bamboo structures that line the beach. Just down the street is Globe Telecom’s newer facility, an anchor point for the Southeast Asia Japan cable system. Large walls surround both stations and the place where cables enter the water is unmarked. On their journey out to sea, they pass the remains of a Spanish galleon, sunk by the Dutch navy in 1600. Discovered in 1992, the shipwreck became one of the most important finds in underwater archeology. A replica, along with a museum and resort, were built on nearby Fortune Island but have since fallen into disrepair.

Entering service in March 1999, this optical cable connects the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company’s station in Batangas with AT&T’s landing point in Guam, where connections are made to several Asia-U.S. networks. It was designed to complement and ease congestion along existing Asian and trans-Pacific cable systems.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: This cable was launched on October 19, 1992, with a press conference at the Philippine Plaza Hotel in Manila. It was part of the $320 million ASEAN Optical-Fiber Submarine Cable Network, which also included lines between Brunei and Singapore, and between two parts of Malaysia across the South China Sea.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: On a rainy November morning in 2013, a French cable team collaborated with a local construction crew to complete Vanuatu’s first underwater fiber-optic connection: a link to Fiji and the Southern Cross network. After surfacing on the black sand beaches of Mele Bay outside Port Vila, the cable runs inland to a modular station, assembled from five prefabricated units roughly the size of shipping containers. A high cinderblock wall surrounds the entire facility, blocking out potential intruders and making it less prominent than nearby medicinal gardens, coffee-roasting plants, and microbreweries. Through physically discrete, the station’s economic and cultural impact was by no means overlooked. Earlier that year, thousands gathered along the Port Vila waterfront to celebrate National Information and Communication Technologies Day and the cable’s impending arrival.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: A popular Japanese name, Emi means “reflect” and “beauty,” apt for the town’s turbulent history and present floriculture. The region suffered a cholera outbreak in the late 1800s, and was bombed and invaded by U.S. forces during the Second World War. Today, flower farms blanket the hills outside the village. In nearby Kamogawa, the Futomi Flower Center contains a garden and greenhouse with over two thousand plant species collected from around the world, from orchids to cacti. This living hub faces the Pacific Ocean just a few miles from the Tata Communications cable station in Emi, which joins Tokyo to the U.S. and the rest of Tata’s global network.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Long before Toyohashi was linked to underwater cable systems, it belonged to a key pedestrian highway network. From the seventeenth to mid-nineteenth century, the town was one of fifty “post stations” or rest stops along the Tōkaidō, widely considered the most important of five government-sponsored roads that joined Tokyo (then known as Edo) to outlying territories. While contemporary signals pass through at the speed of light, travelers on the Tōkaidō paused in Toyohashi to buy supplies, visit teahouses, and find lodging on their journeys between Edo and Kyoto. The stations fell out of use when railroads expanded in the late 1800s, but the route remains a major transit corridor. Opened in 1964, the Tōkaidō Shinkasnsen is the most-traveled high-speed rail line in the world.

The modern two-story cable station and data center, built to withstand severe weather, sits across the road from a rocky beach in the quiet suburb of Sopu, due west of central Nuku’alofa. Between 1978 and 2013, when a fiber-optic link to Fiji was completed, Tonga relied entirely on satellite connections. Internet access was slow, expensive, and used by less than a fifth of the population. But with a capacity six thousand times greater than satellite, the cable is set to lower costs and stimulate business investment, bringing more of the country online than ever before. Although it entered the underwater network only recently, Nuku’alofa has long been a regional hub. The deep natural harbor bounded by coral reefs is still Tonga’s main port and a gateway to the rest of the archipelago. Not far from the sleek landing station, the reefs are littered with the rusted hulls of old fishing vessels carried ashore by past storms.
